# Plan: Card styling overhaul + shopping item history

## Context

Several UX improvements across the shopping and cleaning cards:
- Interactive cards have card-in-card nesting (item rows with borders inside `<ha-card>`) that looks cluttered
- Shopping checkmark looks "already done" (green filled) instead of "click to complete"
- No way to see purchase history for a shopping item
- Compact distribution chart truncates names when count is 0
- Cleaning card week rows should be fully clickable for the details modal

## Files to modify

- `custom_components/hass_flatmate/frontend/hass-flatmate-shopping-card.js` — Remove outer card, restyle check icon, add item click + history modal
- `custom_components/hass_flatmate/frontend/hass-flatmate-cleaning-card.js` — Remove outer card border
- `custom_components/hass_flatmate/frontend/hass-flatmate-distribution-card.js` — Fix compact name truncation
- `custom_components/hass_flatmate/sensor.py` — Add `item_history` data (completed items grouped by name) to ShoppingDataSensor

## Changes

### 1. Remove outer ha-card border from interactive shopping card

Replace `<ha-card>` wrapper with a plain `<div>` or keep `<ha-card>` but remove its default border/shadow. The simplest approach: keep `<ha-card>` (HA expects it) but add CSS to flatten it:

```css
ha-card {
  box-shadow: none;
  border: none;
  background: transparent;
}
```

This removes the outer card chrome. The inner item rows with their borders become the primary visual structure.

### 2. Remove outer ha-card border from interactive cleaning card

Same approach — add to the cleaning card CSS:

```css
ha-card {
  box-shadow: none;
  border: none;
  background: transparent;
}
```

Only for interactive mode (not compact, which doesn't have card-in-card).

### 3. Shopping checkmark icon — change to outline style

Change from `mdi:check-circle-outline` (which HA renders as a circle with checkmark, appearing "done") to `mdi:checkbox-blank-circle-outline` (empty circle) or `mdi:circle-outline`.

Update CSS: remove the green tinted background, use a neutral/subdued style that invites clicking. On hover, tint green to signal the action.

```css
.todo-check {
  color: var(--secondary-text-color);
  border-color: var(--divider-color);
  background: var(--card-background-color);
}
.todo-check:hover {
  color: var(--success-color, #4caf50);
  border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--success-color, #4caf50) 45%, var(--divider-color));
  background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--success-color, #4caf50) 10%, var(--card-background-color));
}
```

### 4. Shopping item click → history modal

#### 4a. Build item_history in sensor.py

In `ShoppingDataSensor.extra_state_attributes`, add `item_history`: a dict mapping normalized item name → list of purchase records, built from completed items in `shopping_items`.

```python
# From coordinator.data["shopping_items"], filter status="completed"
# Group by normalized name (case-insensitive)
# Each entry: { "completed_by_name": str, "completed_at": str (ISO), "completed_by_member_id": int }
# Sort by completed_at descending, limit to 10 per item
# Only include items whose name matches an open item (to avoid sending huge history)
```

#### 4b. Item row click handler (shopping card JS)

Make the `.item-main` area clickable (not the action buttons). On click, open a modal showing purchase history for that item name.

Add state: `_historyModalOpen`, `_historyModalItemName`.

Add to `_buildStateSnapshot`: `history_modal_open`, `history_modal_item_name`.

#### 4c. History modal rendering

